00:59:19.730 --> 00:59:22.230
Some pictures are
better than others.

00:59:22.230 --> 00:59:22.730
No.

00:59:22.730 --> 00:59:28.130
I think that we all have
unpublished pictures.

00:59:28.130 --> 00:59:32.960
And maybe some
unpublished pictures

00:59:32.960 --> 00:59:37.970
are better unseen,
because you want pictures

00:59:37.970 --> 00:59:39.125
to come up to a certain--

00:59:39.125 --> 00:59:41.000
PETER FETTERMAN: Do you
think you're the best

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:42.706
judge of what is your--

00:59:42.706 --> 00:59:44.510
STEVE MCCURRY: No.

00:59:44.510 --> 00:59:48.500
I know you mentioned the picture
by Andre Cartier-Bresson which

00:59:48.500 --> 00:59:51.620
had gone unnoticed largely.

00:59:51.620 --> 00:59:58.024
And you saw it, liked it, and
asked to have a print made.

00:59:58.024 --> 00:59:59.690
And it's a wonderful,
beautiful picture.

00:59:59.690 --> 01:00:00.690
I think it's incredible.

01:00:00.690 --> 01:00:03.110
It's in your gallery.

01:00:03.110 --> 01:00:11.690
So I think that
there's a reason why.

01:00:11.690 --> 01:00:15.110
I think you want your
best work published.

01:00:15.110 --> 01:00:18.980
And I can't think
of a situation where

01:00:18.980 --> 01:00:21.500
I took pictures
which I regretted

01:00:21.500 --> 01:00:24.860
or got published and regretted.

01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:26.690
I can't really think of many.

01:00:26.690 --> 01:00:32.610
There is one instance that comes
to mind where in Bangladesh--

01:00:32.610 --> 01:00:36.230
I think it was during
the War of Independence--

01:00:36.230 --> 01:00:40.040
there were some
photographers who were there.

01:00:40.040 --> 01:00:44.420
And there were these
soldiers that were maybe

01:00:44.420 --> 01:00:47.810
